<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: LOS ANGELES; OK 
EXPECTED FOR NAMING CIVILIAN TO POLICE PANELS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Los Angeles Police Commission is expected to approve a motion today 
clearing the way for a civilian member to join police disciplinary panels, a 
significant step toward implementing a reform approved by voters two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
 Some police officers have expressed reservations about the idea, but 
representatives of the Los Angeles Police Protective League tentatively backed 
it under conditions laid out in an agreement to be considered today by the 
commission.That agreement spells out employment and selection criteria for the 
civilian board members. 
</P>
<P>
 In its study of the LAPD, the Christopher Commission recommended that a 
civilian be included on police boards of rights -- which now are made up of 
three senior officers. The commission's recommendation was approved by city 
voters in 1992 as part of Charter Amendment F. 
</P>
</TEXT>
