<HEADLINE>
<P>
PROSECUTOR URGES JURY TO CONVICT RAPE CASE DEFENDANT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By THOM MROZEK, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A prosecutor urged a jury Tuesday to convict a man on trial for repeatedly 
raping two North Hollywood women in neighboring apartments on consecutive 
nights. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 A Van Nuys Superior Court jury will begin deliberations today in the trial of 
Scott Daniel Artamenko, 24, who faces 19 felony counts stemming from the two 
attacks in an apartment building on Colfax Avenue. 
</P>
<P>
 Often looking directly at the defendant, Deputy Dist. Atty. Steven J. Ipsen 
accused Artamenko of repeated sexual assaults where he was "raping not just her 
body, but also her emotions." 
</P>
<P>
 The first woman, now 44, testified that she was repeatedly raped during the 
early morning hours of June 30 of last year. From the witness stand, she 
tentatively identified Artamenko as the rapist. 
</P>
<P>
 When the first victim heard screaming from a nearby apartment the next 
morning, July 1, she summoned police, according to testimony. Officers knocked 
on the door, and the second woman, who is 30, was able to flee. Artamenko was 
taken into custody after a brief struggle with police. 
</P>
<P>
 Ipsen said that when the first woman and her boyfriend viewed the suspect 
after he was arrested, Artamenko looked at the man and said, "Go ahead, charge 
me so the police will kill me and I won't have to deal with this." 
</P>
<P>
 Describing the similarity of the two attacks, Ipsen said the incidents were "a 
repeated nightmare" similar to the movie "Groundhog Day," where the lead 
character has to live the same day over and over. 
</P>
<P>
 Defense attorney Patricia A. Andreoni-Alcazar stressed that there is 
reasonable doubt that Artamenko committed the first attack. 
</P>
<P>
 "Even on the stand, (the first woman) couldn't be 100% sure my client was the 
attacker," she said. 
</P>
<P>
 Andreoni-Alcazar acknowledged that Artamenko had sex with the second woman, 
but said he was under the influence of alcohol and could not form the intent 
necessary for a criminal conviction. 
</P>
<P>
 If convicted on all 19 counts, Artamenko would face more than 100 years in 
prison. 
</P>
</TEXT>
